Time Series Anaysis on FDIC SDI Dataset¶

This report analyzes FDIC SDI data from 2007 - 2019, focusing on Net Asset variable. ARIMA and ARIMAX model have been applied for forward forecasting, with detrending and de-seasonalizing during pre-precessing to achieve stationary data status.¶

----- Fortuna Zhang, June 2020¶

Time Series Analysis¶

Steps:¶

1. Visualization Exploration: Trend line & Box plot (Economic cycle) 
2. Stationary Test (ADF & KPSS)
3. Detrending (Substract best fit & Multiplicative Decompose)
4. Deseasonalizing 
5. Autocorrelation & Partial Autocorrelation 
6. ARIMA Model Prediction
7. Exponential Smoothing Prediction
8. GARCH Model Prediction
9. Trend Scanning Labelling
10. ARIMAX Model Prediction

#  ADF Test
print('\nNetAsset: Stationarity test 1')

    print('Critial Values:')
    print(f'   {key}, {value}')

for key, value in result[3].items():
    print('Critial Values:')
    print(f'   {key}, {value}')

For NetAsset:
ADF test: Since p-value is larger than 0.1, we cannot reject thenull hypothesisthat there is a unit root/data is non-stationary.
KPSS test: Since p-value is less than 0.05, we reject thenull hypothesisthat the data is stationary.
Both tests indicate the original Net Asset time-series data is non-stationary.

Detrend - two methods¶

Method 1: Subtract the line of best fit¶

In [16]:
# Method 1 - Using scipy: Subtract the line of best fit
from scipy import signal

f = plt.figure()
plt.plot(detrended1)
plt.title('Net Asset detrended by subtracting the least squares fit', fontsize=10)

After detrending, Net Asset time-series data has concave upward, trend component has succesfully been removed. There may be a parabola in the residuals, suggesting that perhaps a polynomial fit may have done a better job.

Method2: Multiplicative or Additive decompose (compare)¶

Triple Components

In [18]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
from dateutil.parser import parse

# Multiplicative Decomposition 
result_mul = seasonal_decompose(dategroup.netasset, model='multiplicative', extrapolate_trend='freq')

# Additive Decomposition
result_add = seasonal_decompose(dategroup.netasset, model='additive', extrapolate_trend='freq')

# Plot
fig = plt.figure()
fig.set_figheight(20) # optional setting the height of the image
fig.set_figwidth(20) # optional setting the width of the image

# fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True)
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize': (10,5)})
result_mul.plot().suptitle('Multiplicative Decompose', fontsize=15)

result_add.plot().suptitle('Additive Decompose', fontsize=15)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1440x1440 with 0 Axes>

For Net Asset data, we choose Multiplicative Decompose method because the magnitude of the seasonal pattern in the data depends on the magnitude of the data, and residuals are less vary with the level of the time series compared to additive method.

# Method2: Using statmodels: Subtracting the Trend Component.
# https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/generated/statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.seasonal_decompose.html
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,figsize=(15,7),sharex=True)


result_mul2 = seasonal_decompose(dategroup.netasset, model='multiplicative', extrapolate_trend='freq')
detrended2 = dategroup.netasset.values / result_mul2.trend
detrended2.plot(ax=ax[0],color='blue')
ax[0].set_title('Net Asset detrended by dividing the trend component', fontsize=16); 

result_mul2a = seasonal_decompose(dategroup.netasset, model='additive', extrapolate_trend='freq')
detrended2a = dategroup.netasset.values - result_mul2a.trend
detrended2a.plot(ax=ax[1],color='red')
ax[1].set_title('Net Asset detrended by subtracting the trend component', fontsize=16);

Out[25]:

The autocorrelation for an observation and an observation at a prior time step is comprised of both the direct correlation and indirect correlations. These indirect correlations are a linear function of the correlation of the observation, with observations at intervening time steps.
A partial autocorrelation is a summary of the relationship between an observation in a time series with observations at prior time steps with the relationships of intervening observations removed, only describes the direct relationship between an observation and its lag.
Autocorrelation displays a sharp cutoff after lag3, thus we can consider adding MA term, q=3.
Partial Autocorrelation displays rare variation around zero, thus we don't need to add AR term, p=0.

Exponential smoothing method¶

In [37]:
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

train_st = deseasonalizedNet.ix[:-8]
test_st = deseasonalizedNet.ix[-8:]

model = ExponentialSmoothing(train_st, trend="add", seasonal="add", seasonal_periods=4)
model2 = ExponentialSmoothing(train_st, trend="add", seasonal="add", seasonal_periods=4, damped=True)
fit = model.fit()
pred = fit.forecast(8)
fit2 = model2.fit()
pred2 = fit2.forecast(8)

sse1 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(test_st.values - pred.values)))
sse2 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(test_st.values - pred2.values)))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
ax.plot(train_st.index, train_st.values);
ax.plot(test_st.index, test_st.values, label='truth');
ax.plot(test_st.index, pred, linestyle='--', color='#ff7823', label="w/o damping (RMSE={:0.2f}, AIC={:0.2f})".format(sse1, fit.aic));
ax.plot(test_st.index, pred2, linestyle='--', color='#3c763d', label="damped (RMSE={:0.2f}, AIC={:0.2f})".format(sse2, fit2.aic)); 
ax.legend();
ax.set_title("Holt-Winter's Seasonal Smoothing");

RMSE as good as SARIMA model, and AIC is even lower, thus exponential smoothing is a little bit better for net asset prediction

Conclusion for univariate model prediction¶

Detrend and Deseasonalize:¶

Detrending by deviding trend component/multiplicative performs better than substracting best fit on Net Asset data. Deseasonlizing improves stationary condition even more.

SARIMA Model:¶

Using SARIMA model, for now 2-step prediction using past 3 lag moving average and 1 differencing is the best model, and RSME is low at 0.01, AIC is -309.6. Though the training set is large and may be due to overfitting.

Exponential Smoothing (Holt-Winter's seasonal smoothing) Model:¶

Exponential Smoothing RMSE is as low as SARIMA at 0.01, and damped AIC is even lower to -388.35. Therefore exponential smoothing is better than SARIMA model prediction.

ARIMAX multivariate model¶

Although exponential smoothing model generates better prediction accuracy in the univariate model, it cannot include more than one x variable thus we choose ARIMAX model for multivariate x inputs.
For ARIMAX multivariate model, we add dep (total deposits)& eeffr (efficiency ratio) as exogenous variables, they meet the assumption of ARIMAX that they all have causal relationship with net asset, while dep accounts for tangible asset and eeffr accounts for intangible asset.

Granger-causality test
The test is whether the first variable is caused by the second variable.

ax.fill_between(ym_test.index, lower_bounds, upper_bounds, color='#ff7823', alpha=0.3, label="confidence interval (95%)");
ax.legend();
ax.set_title("SARIMAX with  eeffr");

RMSE is even higher in the SARIMAX model with dep and eeffr, suggesting that these two variables have not improve prediction accuracy of net aseet.

import statsmodels.api as sm1

def tValLinR(close):
# tValue from a linear trend
    x=np.ones((close.shape[0],2))
    x[:,1]=np.arange(close.shape[0])
    ols=sm1.OLS(close,x).fit()
    return ols.tvalues[1]

def getBinsFromTrend(molecule,close,span):
# 
# Derive labels from the sign of t-value of linear trend
# Output includes:
# - t1: End time for the identified trend
# - tVal: t-value associated with the estimated trend coefficient
# - bin: Sign of the trend
# 
    out=pd.DataFrame(index=molecule,columns=['t1','tVal','bin'])
    hrzns=range(*span)
    for dt0 in molecule:
        df0=pd.Series()
        iloc0=close.index.get_loc(dt0)
        if iloc0+max(hrzns)>close.shape[0]:continue
        for hrzn in hrzns:
            dt1=close.index[iloc0+hrzn-1]
            df1=close.loc[dt0:dt1]
            df0.loc[dt1]=tValLinR(df1.values)
        dt1=df0.replace([-np.inf,np.inf,np.nan],0).abs().idxmax()
        out.loc[dt0,['t1','tVal','bin']]=df0.index[-1],df0[dt1],np.sign(df0[dt1]) # prevent leakage
    out['t1']=pd.to_datetime(out['t1'])
    out['bin']=pd.to_numeric(out['bin'],downcast='signed')
    return out.dropna(subset=['bin'])

An indicator of an institutions primary specialization in terms of asset concentration. note: (groups are hierarchical and mutually exclusive):
1 international Specialization Institutions with assets greater than 10 billion and more than 25 percent of total assets in foreign offices.
2 Agricultural Specialization Banks with agricultural production loans plus real estate loans secured by farmland in excess of 25 percent of total loans and leases.
3 Credit-card Specialization Institutions with credit-card loans plus securitized receivables in excess of 50 percent of total assets plus securitized receivables.
4 Commercial Lending Specialization Institutions with commercial and industrial loans, plus real estate construction and development loans, plus loans secured by commercial real estate properties in excess of 25 percent of total assets.
5 Mortgage Lending Specialization Institutions with residential mortgage loans, plus mortgage-backed securities, in excess of 50 percent of total assets.
6 Consumer Lending Specialization Institutions with residential mortgage loans, plus credit-card loans, plus other loans to individuals, in excess of 50 percent of total assets.
7 Other Specialized $1 Billion Institutions with assets greater than 1 billion that do not meet any of the definitions above, they have significant lending activity with no identified asset concentrations.
